{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507774"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:57:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:57:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2669"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583369"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:14:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:14:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2669"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2669"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.2,0.04,0.53,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2669"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52032"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2669"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2669"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"451"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42542"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52032"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with an ulcerated erythematous lesion on his left cheek. He reports that the lesion appeared suddenly about two months ago and has been intermittently bleeding without any preceding trauma. He has a medical history of end-stage renal disease, for which he underwent a renal transplant 10 years ago. He takes regular immunosuppressive medications post-transplant. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has smoked 20 cigarettes per day for the last 50 years. He works as a farmer, though reports fastidiously applying sunscreen while working outdoors, always wearing a hat and long-sleeved clothing, and avoiding sun exposure in the middle of the day. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an ulcerated, erythematous lesion on his left cheek. A diagnosis of squamous cell carcinoma is made.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the greatest risk factor for the development of squamous cell carcinoma in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fair skin","Ultraviolet B exposure","Advanced age","Immunosuppressive therapy","Smoking history"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunosuppressive therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the greatest risk factor for the development of cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (cSCC) in this patient. Chronic suppression of the immune system, typically used in transplant recipients, significantly impairs the ability of T cells to identify and destroy tumour cells. This puts patients on long-term immunosuppression at a much higher risk of developing skin cancers, particularly cSCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltraviolet B exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-known risk factor for cSCC. However, this patient\u0027s history of proper sun protection (regular sunscreen use, protective clothing, and avoiding midday sun) makes this less likely to be the most significant risk factor in his case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFair skin\u003C/strong\u003E is also a risk factor for cSCC, as individuals with less melanin are more susceptible to UV damage. However, given the patient\u0027s history of immunosuppression, this is not the most significant risk factor in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvanced age\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed a risk factor for cSCC, as cumulative sun damage and decreased immune function occur over time. However, the patient\u0027s history of significant immunosuppression outweighs age as a risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking history\u003C/strong\u003E, while a risk factor for many cancers, has not been conclusively demonstrated to be a significant risk factor for cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma. Its impact on cSCC risk is much less than that of immunosuppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while all these factors may contribute to the patient\u0027s risk of developing cSCC, immunosuppressive therapy stands out as the most significant risk factor in this case. Patients on long-term immunosuppression require regular and thorough skin checks, as they are at increased risk of developing skin cancers, particularly cSCC.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The most common malignancy to develop in those on long-term immunosuppression is cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma.","Immunosuppressive therapy significantly increases the risk of developing cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma by impairing T cell function."],"references":["Plasmeijer EI, Sachse MM, Gebhardt C, Geusau A, Bouwes Bavinck JN. Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (cSCC) and immunosurveillance\u2013the impact of immunosuppression on frequency of cSCC. Journal of the European Academy of Dermatology and Venereology. 2019 Dec;33:33-7. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31833604/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2669"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T09:40:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T09:41:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2669"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52032"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","